Example
Your doctor tells you that you have tested positive for a serious but rare (1/10000) disease. This test (T) is correct to 99% (1% false positive & 1% false negative results). What does this mean for you?

\[
\begin{flalign}
P(D|T) = \frac{P(T|D) P(D)}{P(T)} = \frac{P(T|D) P(D)}{P(T|D) P(D) + P(T| \neg D) P( \neg D)} &&
\end{flalign}
\]


\[
\begin{flalign}
P(D) = 0.0001 \quad P(T|D) = 0.99 \quad P(T | \neg D) = 0.01 &&
\end{flalign}
\]


\[
\begin{flalign}
P(D|T) = \frac{0.99 x 0.0001}{0.99 x 0.0001 + 0.01 x 0.9999} = \frac{0.000099}{0.010088} ‚âà 0.01 &&
\end{flalign}
\]


Bottom line: if the inaccuracy of the test is much greater than the frequency of occurrence of the disease, then a positive result is not as threatening as one might think.

Multiple evidence
A dentist‚Äôs probe catches in the aching tooth of a patient.
Using Bayes‚Äô rule, we can calculate:
\[
\begin{flalign}
P(Cav | Catch) = 0.95 &&
\end{flalign}
\]

But how does the combined evidence help?


With the help of Bayes‚Äô rule, the dentist could conclude:
\[
\begin{flalign}
P(Cav | Toothache \land Catch) = \frac{P(Toothache \land Catch|Cav)P(Cav)}{P(Toothache \land Catch)} &&
\end{flalign}
\]


\[
\begin{flalign}
P(Cav | Toothache \land Catch) = \alpha{P(Toothache \land Catch|Cav)P(Cav)} && (2.0)
\end{flalign}
\]

Conditional independence
The general definition of conditional independence of two variables \(X\) and \(Y\) given a third variable \(Z\) is:
\[
\begin{flalign}
P(X,Y|Z) = P(X|Z)P(Y|Z) &&
\end{flalign}
\]

In the dentist example, it seems reasonable to assert conditional independence of the variables \(Toothache\) and \(Catch\) given \(Cav\), thus we can insert equation (2.1) into (2.0) leading to
\[
\begin{flalign}
P(Cav | Toothache \land Catch) = \alpha{P(Toothache | Cav) P(Catch | Cav)P(Cav)} &&
\end{flalign}
\]

Naive Bayes classifier
A naive Bayes model reflects a pattern in which a single cause (\(C\)) directly influences a number of effects (\(E_n\)), all of which are conditionally independent, given the cause:
\[
\begin{flalign}
P(C|E_1,...,E_n) = \frac{P(E_1|C)*P(E_2|C)...P(E_n)*P(C)}{P(E_1)*P(E_2)...P(E_n)} &&
\end{flalign}
\]
\[
\begin{flalign}
P(C|E_1,...,E_n) = P(C) \prod_i P(E_i|C) && (3.0)
\end{flalign}
\]
To use these models, we can apply the generalized normalization equation to obtain the probability of the cause given some observed effects.
\[
\begin{flalign}
P(C|e) = \alpha \sum_y P(C,e,y) && (3.1)
\end{flalign}
\]
\(E = e\) are the observed effects, while the remaining effect variables \(Y\) are unobserved.

